article.headline: Sparks drop third straight, still missing Leslie
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Andrea Stinson helped the Charlotte Sting out
of its worst slump of the season, and reached a career milestone in
the process.

Stinson scored 23 points and became the second player in WNBA
history to surpass 3,000 points in an 84-73 victory over the Los
Angeles Sparks 84-73 Saturday night, as the Sting won for just the
second time in seven games since the All-Star break.

"We were aggressive offensively and kind of kept them on their
heels and didn't give them a lot of transition baskets," Charlotte
coach Trudi Lacey said.

Stinson, who has 3,011 points during her seven-year WNBA career,
is second to Los Angeles' injured center Lisa Leslie, who has
3,533.

"It's the love of the game for me," Stinson said. "I am proud
of myself and my teammates helped me get there."

DeLisha Milton scored 23 and Mwadi Mabika 21 for the two-time
defending champion Sparks (18-8), who lost their third consecutive
game and saw their lead in the Western Conference cut to two games
over Houston (15-9).

"I can tell what we didn't do -- you can just look at the board
right there at the top and it would sum up the whole, entire game,
especially the first half," Milton said, referring to the words
"Play hard," written on a dry erase board in the team's locker
room.

"We're tired of talking in here," Milton said. "Either you're
going to bring your best to the game or practice or whatever it is,
or you're not. If you're not, we're going to lose because it's
going to take everybody."

Los Angeles is "doing things that are uncharacteristic of
Sparks basketball," Milton said.

"Selfishness that's going on, no execution, no defense,"
Milton said. "Michael Cooper is our coach. He's a defensive guru.
That's all he knows and we can't go out there and be an example of
our coach while we're out there. I'm at a loss for words."

Allison Feaster added 21, Dawn Staley 15 points and nine assists
and Tammy Sutton-Brown 14 points for Charlotte (14-11), which moved
a half-game past Indiana (13-11) into second place in the Eastern
Conference, 4{ games behind Detroit (18-6).

Los Angeles played its eighth consecutive game without Leslie,
the reigning league MVP, who hurt her right knee in the All-Star
game July 12. The Sparks are 3-5 without her.

The Sting, who led 40-31 at halftime, made it 54-39 with 15:05
left as Stinson and Sutton-Brown each scored four during a 9-2 run.

Los Angeles responded by outscoring Charlotte 11-4 over a 4:02
span, with Mabika scoring seven and Milton four, cutting the
deficit to 58-50 with 10:15 remaining.

Staley began a 10-2 run with a 3-pointer and Feaster scored the
next seven points, giving the Sting a 68-52 lead with 7:14 to play.
Charlotte led by as many as 18 and at least nine for the rest of
the way.

The Sparks announced before the game they signed forward Vanessa
Nygaard for the remainder of the season.
